## Propagating Trace Context Across RabbitMQ

The issue is that RabbitMQ doesn't automatically propagate W3C trace context. You need to **inject** context into message headers on publish and **extract** it on consume.

### Publisher (Service A)

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Define a shared ActivitySource
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("OrderEvent Publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current context into message headers
DistributedContextPropagator.Current.Inject(
    activity, props.Headers, static (carrier, key, value) =>
    {
        if (carrier is IDictionary<string, object> headers)
            headers[key] = value;
    });

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

### Consumer (Service B)

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");

// In your consumer callback:
var parentContext = default(ActivityContext);

DistributedContextPropagator.Current.ExtractTraceIdAndState(
    ea.BasicProperties.Headers,
    static (carrier, key) =>
    {
        if (carrier is IDictionary<string, object> h && h.TryGetValue(key, out var val))
            return val is byte[] bytes ? Encoding.UTF8.GetString(bytes) : val?.ToString();
        return null;
    },
    out var traceParent, out var traceState);

if (ActivityContext.TryParse(traceParent, traceState, out var ctx))
    parentContext = ctx;

using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
    "OrderEvent Process",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentContext);

// Process the message — this activity is now linked to Service A's trace
```

### Wire it up in `Program.cs` (both services)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")   // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

### Why this works

| Step | What happens |
|---|---|
| **Inject** | `traceparent` / `tracestate` headers are written to `IBasicProperties.Headers` |
| **Extract** | Consumer reads those headers and reconstructs the parent `ActivityContext` |
| **StartActivity** | The consumer's span becomes a **child** of the producer's span → single end-to-end trace |

**Key gotcha:** RabbitMQ stores header values as `byte[]`, so the extract callback must decode with `Encoding.UTF8.GetString`. Missing that is the most common reason extraction silently fails.
